      "question": "Assertion (A): For a polynomial $p(x) = x^3 - 3x^2 + 5x - 3$, if the division by $g(x) = x^2 - 2$ results in a remainder $r(x)$, then the degree of $r(x)$ is $1$. \n\nReason (R): According to the division algorithm for polynomials, if $p(x) = g(x)q(x) + r(x)$, then either $r(x) = 0$ or the degree of $r(x)$ must be strictly less than the degree of $g(x)$.",
      "answer": "(A)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Identify the degree of the divisor $g(x) = x^2 - 2$, which is $2$.",
          "Recall the division algorithm: $p(x) = g(x)q(x) + r(x)$, where $r(x) = 0$ or $\\text{deg}(r(x)) < \\text{deg}(g(x))$.",
          "Perform the division of $x^3 - 3x^2 + 5x - 3$ by $x^2 - 2$. The quotient is $x - 3$ and the remainder is $7x - 9$.",
          "The degree of the remainder $r(x) = 7x - 9$ is $1$. Since $1 < 2$, the condition is satisfied.",
          "Both assertions are true and the reason provides the fundamental definition used to verify the assertion."
        ],
        "derivation": "$p(x) = x^3 - 3x^2 + 5x - 3 \\\\ g(x) = x^2 - 2 \\\\ x^3 - 3x^2 + 5x - 3 = (x^2 - 2)(x - 3) + (7x - 9) \\\\ \\text{deg}(r(x)) = \\text{deg}(7x - 9) = 1 \\\\ \\text{deg}(g(x)) = 2 \\\\ 1 < 2 \\text{ is true.}$"
      },
